article.description:
Playing its first game in 11 days, No. 2
Louisiana State shot 58.5 percent from the field and beat Ohio
85-57 Wednesday night in the second game of the
womenscollegehoops.com Classic.
article.headline: Lady Tigers off to best start since 1996-97
article.linkText: Third-ranked LSU shows little rust in win over Ohio
article.story:
BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Ohio University coach Lynn Bria now
feels Louisiana State has earned its way among the elite teams in
women's college basketball.

	   DeTrina White had 14 points and 10 rebounds and the
(No. 3 ESPN/USA Today, No. 2 AP) Lady Tigers shook off the rust of an 11-day layoff in
an 85-57 rout of the Bobcats in the second game of the
womenscollegehoops.com Classic on Wednesday night.

	   LSU (7-0) is off to its best start since winning the first 14
games in 1996-97, and improved to 13-0 in regular season tournament
games at home.

	   The Lady Tigers will play Louisville, which beat New Orleans
56-47, on Thursday for the tournament championship.

	   LSU forced Ohio (1-6) into a season-high 27 turnovers and held a
decisive 33-21 rebounding edge.

	   "They are a very good team, no question about it,'' Bria said.
"Once their offense catches up to their defense, they might be a
Final Four team.''

	   LSU shot 69.7 percent (23-of-33) in the first half and 58.5 for
the game.

	   White, a fifth-year senior who sat out the 2001-02 season with a
stress fracture in her left foot, extended her school record with
her 26th double-double.

	   Aiysha Smith scored 13 of her 15 points in the first half, while
Seimone Augustus added 12 and Roneeka Hodges 10. Ten of the 13 Lady
Tigers scored.

	   "We really worked on a lot of things during the week we had
off,'' White said. "One of our main goals was to come in, play
hard in the first five minutes and get off on the right track, and
tonight, we pretty much did.''

	   LSU took a 6-0 lead before Andrea Johnson got Ohio on the board
with the first of her four 3-pointers in the first half. Johnson's
25-footer from the top of the key pulled the Bobcats within 17-11
at the 11:18 mark of the opening half.

	   LSU put the game out of reach with a 10-0 run just after the
midway point of the opening half. KeKe Tardy started the run with a
three-point play, and a layup by White ended the run and made it
33-13 with 7:30 remaining in the half.

	   Johnson, who finished with 24 points, capped a 7-0 run with her
fourth 3-pointer that made it 38-22 with 4:17 left in the first
half, but that would be as close as the Bobcats would get the rest
of the way.

	   The Lady Tigers responded with a 12-2 run. Two layups by White
and two short jumpers by Augustus gave LSU a 50-24 lead en route to
a 51-28 halftime advantage.

	   The 51 points were the most by LSU in a half this season, as the
Lady Tigers shot 69.7 percent (23-of-33) from the field in the
opening 20 minutes.
	   
LSU's lead never fell below 21 points in the second half and got
as big as 83-47 on a jumper by Wendlyn Jones with 4:14 remaining.
